        "body": "Having established the preparation of the purification agent, the chapter turns to its application. Verses 11-16 catalog the forms of corpse-impurity with remarkable comprehensiveness. Direct touch of a corpse (v.11) is the primary case. But the law extends further: proximity in a shared tent when someone dies (v.14), the uncovered vessels in that tent (v.15), and any contact in an open field with a slain person, a naturally dead person, a human bone, or a grave (v.16). The seven-day impurity is identical across all cases. The degree of proximity does not reduce the severity of the contamination.\n\nThe tent scenario (vv.14-15) is especially significant. When a person dies inside a tent, everyone inside is defiled — not because they touched the body, but because they shared the same enclosed space. Open vessels without a fastened covering become unclean; sealed vessels are protected. The spatial logic models the theology: death's contamination radiates outward within its sphere. Spiritual deadness is not only transmitted by direct contact; it spreads through shared environments, uncovered exposures, sustained proximity.\n\nThe open-field scenario (v.16) extends the principle to the battlefield and to the burial ground. A bone — the most durable remnant of a human body — transmits full seven-day impurity. A grave, even without visible remains, defiles whoever contacts it. This is the background to Jesus's denunciation of the Pharisees as 'whitewashed tombs' (Matthew 23:27) — those who come into contact with them are defiled without knowing it, precisely because the contamination is hidden. Luke 11:44 makes the connection even more explicit: 'You are like concealed tombs, and the people who walk over them are unaware.' The red heifer law provides the subtext for some of the sharpest critiques in the Gospels.\n\nThe repeated seven-day duration — unvaried across all cases — establishes a principle: death's defilement is total, not graded. Minor exposure and major exposure produce the same legal status. In typological terms, the New Testament counterpart is the recognition that no sinner is 'less dead' than another. Ephesians 2:1 does not grade spiritual death by degree: 'you were dead in your trespasses and sins.' The condition is categorical, not scalar."
